First write this following member function:
	•	MakeDeposit: this function should take a username (e.g. “Prof”), an asset (e.g. “BTC”), and an amount (e.g. 100). The function does not return anything, but should store the information that the deposit occurred to a user’s portfolio. A portfolio is a record of the assets a user possesses on the exchange that are not involved in any open orders. In the example, Prof is depositing 100 BTC (Bitcoins) into the exchange.

void Exchange::MakeDeposit(const std::string &username, const std::string &asset, int amount) {
  // Find the user's account
  UserAccount *user_account = FindUserAccount(username);
  if (user_account == nullptr) {
    std::cerr << "Error: User account not found\n";
    return;
  }

  // Update the user's portfolio
  user_account->AddToPortfolio(asset, amount);

  // Print a message indicating the deposit was successful
  std::cout << "Deposit of " << amount << " " << asset << " successful for user " << username << "\n";
}

Certainly! One way to do this is to change our `UserAccount` objects from a map of assets to an unordered_map of asset names to amounts (i.e. how many units of each asset the user has). Then, we can create a new `UserAccount` object automatically in the `MakeDeposit` function if one doesn't already exist for the given username. Here's the modified code for the `MakeDeposit` function:

```
void Exchange::MakeDeposit(const std::string &username, const std::string &asset, int amount) {
  // Check if the user already has an account on the exchange
  auto user_account_iter = users.find(username);
  if (user_account_iter == users.end()) {
    // Create a new account for the user
    users[username] = UserAccount();
    std::cout << "Created new account for user " << username << "\n";
  }

  // Update the user's portfolio
  users[username].AddToPortfolio(asset, amount);

  // Print a message indicating the deposit was successful
  std::cout << "Deposit of " << amount << " " << asset << " successful for user " << username << "\n";
}
``` 

In this code, `users` is an unordered_map that maps usernames to `UserAccount` objects. If a username is not found in the map, we create a new empty `UserAccount` and add it to the map. Then we call `AddToPortfolio` on the `UserAccount` to update the user's holdings of the given asset.

